    <h2 id="why-folic-acid">Why Folic Acid Is the Most Critical Prenatal Nutrient</h2>

    <p>Folic acid (vitamin B9) is essential for DNA synthesis, cell division, and neural tube development. The neural tube — which becomes the brain and spinal cord — forms during the first 28 days after conception, often before many women are even aware they are pregnant. Adequate folate intake during this critical window prevents 50-70% of neural tube defects (NTDs), including spina bifida and anencephaly. This is why the CDC recommends that all women of childbearing age consume 400mcg of folic acid daily, whether or not they are planning a pregnancy.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">50-70%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of neural tube defects are preventable with adequate folate intake before and during early pregnancy. The neural tube closes by <strong>day 28 after conception</strong> — supplementation must begin before this window to be effective.</p>
    </div>

    <p>However, there is a critical nuance most supplement guides miss: not all folate forms are equal. Standard folic acid must be enzymatically converted into its active form (5-methyltetrahydrofolate, or 5-MTHF) before the body can use it. Approximately 30-40% of the population carries MTHFR gene variants that reduce this conversion efficiency by 30-70%. For these individuals, supplementing with methylfolate — the already-active form — is significantly more effective.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Folic Acid (Synthetic)</strong>
        <p>The most common supplemental form. Must be converted to 5-MTHF by the MTHFR enzyme. Works well for the ~60% of people without MTHFR variants. Inexpensive and widely available. Used in most fortified foods and prenatal vitamins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Methylfolate (5-MTHF)</strong>
        <p>The biologically active form. Bypasses MTHFR conversion entirely. Works for 100% of the population regardless of genetic status. Increasingly preferred by clinicians for prenatal supplementation. Also labeled as L-methylfolate, Metafolin, or Quatrefolic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>MTHFR Gene Variants</strong>
        <p>C677T variant (30-40% of population): reduces enzyme activity by ~35% heterozygous, ~70% homozygous. A1298C variant (20-30%): milder reduction. Compound heterozygous (both variants): similar to C677T homozygous. A genetic test can identify your status.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Folate vs Folic Acid</strong>
        <p>"Folate" refers to the natural B9 found in food. "Folic acid" is the synthetic supplement form. "Methylfolate" is the active coenzyme form. All three supply vitamin B9, but bioavailability and conversion requirements differ significantly. For supplements, methylfolate is the most universally effective choice.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2014 systematic review in the <em>American Journal of Epidemiology</em> analyzed 41 studies and confirmed that <strong>folic acid supplementation reduces neural tube defect risk by 69%</strong>. The protective effect was dose-dependent, with 400-800mcg daily providing optimal prevention. The same review noted that supplementation beginning at least 1 month before conception produced the strongest protective effect.</p>
      <cite>American Journal of Epidemiology, 2014 — 41 studies, meta-analysis</cite>
    </div>

