    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Folic Acid Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between folic acid and methylfolate?</summary>
      <p>Folic acid is the synthetic form that must be converted to its active form (5-MTHF) by the MTHFR enzyme. Methylfolate is the already-active form that bypasses conversion entirely. Approximately 30-40% of the population carries MTHFR gene variants that reduce folic acid conversion by 30-70%. For these individuals, methylfolate is significantly more effective.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is MTHFR and how does it affect folate supplementation?</summary>
      <p>MTHFR is the gene encoding the enzyme that converts folic acid to active methylfolate. The C677T variant (30-40% of population) reduces enzyme activity by up to 70% in homozygous carriers. For these individuals, methylfolate supplementation bypasses the compromised enzyme entirely. A genetic test can identify your MTHFR status.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much folic acid do I need during pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>The CDC recommends 400mcg daily for all women of reproductive age. ACOG recommends 600mcg during pregnancy. Women with a history of neural tube defects may need 4,000mcg daily. Most gummies provide 400-800mcg per serving, which falls within the recommended range for routine prenatal supplementation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I start taking folic acid before pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>Begin at least 1-3 months before conception. The neural tube forms during the first 28 days after conception — often before many women know they are pregnant. The CDC recommends all women of childbearing age take 400mcg daily, regardless of whether they are actively trying to conceive.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take too much folic acid?</summary>
      <p>The tolerable upper limit for synthetic folic acid is 1,000mcg (1mg) per day. Exceeding this may mask B12 deficiency. However, this limit applies specifically to synthetic folic acid, not methylfolate, which does not accumulate in unmetabolized form. Most gummies provide 400-800mcg, within safe limits.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do folic acid gummies work as well as prenatal pills?</summary>
      <p>Yes, when properly dosed. The gummy format does not reduce folate bioavailability. However, standalone folic acid gummies may lack the iron, DHA, and calcium found in comprehensive prenatal multivitamins. Ensure you are getting these nutrients from other sources if using a standalone product.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is methylfolate better than folic acid for everyone?</summary>
      <p>Methylfolate works for 100% of the population regardless of MTHFR status. If you do not carry MTHFR variants, both forms are equally effective. Since many people have not been tested, methylfolate is the safer default choice. The only consideration is cost — methylfolate is 20-40% more expensive.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What foods are high in natural folate?</summary>
      <p>Dark leafy greens, legumes, asparagus, Brussels sprouts, beets, avocado, and citrus fruits. However, food folate has approximately 50% lower bioavailability than supplemental forms. Supplementation is recommended during pregnancy even with a folate-rich diet.</p>
    </details>

